{
  "doc_id": "44387",
  "text": "Turicibacter, a member of the Erysipelotrichaceae family, which was higher in WKY, rats has been associated with high-fat diets [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Lachnospiraceae have also been reported to be increased in response to high-fat diets [CITATION_3] . Other taxa that have been shown to respond to high-fat diets include Blautia, Ruminococcus, and Dorea [CITATION_4] , and all differed between WKY and SD rats in our study. In addition to its well-known role for producing lactic acid from fermentation of carbohydrates, Lactobacillus, which was increased in WKY relative to SD rats, is also known to express bile salt hydrolases. Bacterial bile salt hydrolase activity can influence lipid metabolism, weight gain, and cholesterol levels through a variety of mechanisms including altering host signaling pathways and bile salt recirculation and increasing de novo synthesis of bile salts produced from cholesterol [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . Our results suggest that differences in the microbiota between SD and WKY rats may have a functional significance for lipid metabolism and response to dietary fat.",
